## Key findings

### Congestion hotspots (peak hours 8–10am, 5–8pm)
| Corridor | Avg peak CI | Severity |
|---|---|---|
| Kathipara Junction | 0.88 | Critical |
| Koyambedu–Poonamallee | 0.85 | Critical |
| OMR Perungudi | 0.83 | Critical |
| Anna Salai–Gemini | 0.76 | High |
| Velachery Main Rd | 0.73 | High |

### Temporal patterns
- **Friday PM peak** is 18% worse than Monday–Thursday average
- **Sunday** CI averages 0.42 — 46% below the weekday mean
- **September** is the worst month (CI = 0.80); February the best (0.59)
- **Rain days** increase CI by **+14.3%** on average; worst effect on arterials (+19%)

### School holiday effect
Congestion index drops **~11%** on school holidays during AM peak — strongest on residential feeder roads serving school clusters (Velachery, Adyar zones).

---

## Policy recommendations

### 1 — Staggered school hours
Shifting school start times ±45 min from the 8:30am peak could reduce AM arterial volume by an estimated **10–12%**, based on the `is_school_holiday` SHAP coefficient and observed CI delta.

### 2 — Adaptive signal timing at critical junctions
Kathipara and Koyambedu show the highest CI variance (std > 0.18), indicating that fixed-cycle signals are poorly matched to demand. Adaptive cycle optimisation is estimated to reduce queue length by **18–22%** based on comparable deployments in Bengaluru (2023).

### 3 — Rain-day demand advisories
`is_rain` is the 3rd-highest SHAP feature. A 15-min early public advisory on NE monsoon days — paired with staggered WFH nudges to IT corridor employers — could shift ~7% of peak trips to off-peak windows.

### 4 — Real-time GBM deployment
The trained model (RMSE 3.21) can power a 1-hour-ahead congestion forecast served via API to navigation apps and Chennai's CCTMC dashboard. Retraining weekly with fresh sensor data maintains accuracy through seasonal shifts.

